>>8621712
"Good" is extremely relative, especially when it comes to oldschool science fiction. Though, this is from 1978, so it'll have a lot of conventions we are used to, at least.

But science fiction is a terribly broad genre, especially oldschool science fiction. This stuff looks a little pulpy, which is a genre that basically doesn't exist anymore, except for hipsters paying homage to it. Poorly. And pulp itself was used by writers who wanted to do serious stuff, but couldn't find an entry into the regular market.

Though, The Wanderer apparently won the Hugo Award. But that just goes to show you can never really tell.

You also get stuff like Cordwainer Smith, who has a short story where a man abuses time travel to evolve a planet of cat people with a central ethos about protecting him, so they can help him fight off gay, transgender space pirates.

Not his strongest story, but entertaining. Point is, science fiction unifies a lot of styles. As a genre, it's based around it's speculative nature rather than "it's about crime or romance". Personally, I think that diversity has taken a bit of a nose-dive in recent years. I've tried reading modern writers, but it's not for me.
